<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="perturbation-definition">
  <statement>
    <p>
      In 
      <url href="https://web.uvic.ca/~tbazett/diffyqs/auteq_section.html#auteq_section">
        Section 1.6
      </url>, you read the following sentence:
    </p>

    <blockquote>
    <p>
      <m>x = A</m> is “stable” in that small perturbations in <m>x</m> do not lead to substantially
      different solutions as <m>t</m> grows.
    </p>
    </blockquote>
    
      <p>
      What is meant by the word <em>perturbation</em> in this context?
      </p>

  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      In this context, a <em>perturbation</em> means a small change in the initial value of the solution.
      That is, instead of starting exactly at the equilibrium value <m>x(0)=A</m>, we begin with a
      nearby initial condition such as <m>x(0)=A+\varepsilon</m> for some small number
      <m>\varepsilon</m>.  The question is how this small deviation affects the long‑term behavior
      of the solution curve.
    </p>

    <p>
      When an equilibrium <m>x=A</m> is described as “stable,” it means that these small
      perturbations—small changes to the starting value—do <em>not</em> lead to solutions that drift far
      away from <m>A</m> as <m>t</m> increases.  The nearby solutions remain close to the equilibrium
      curve, reflecting the intuitive idea that the system “pulls” the solution back toward
       </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-autonomous-1">
  <title>Identifying an Autonomous Equation</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Which of the following differential equations is <em>autonomous</em>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\displaystyle y' = y(3 - y)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. An autonomous equation has the form <m>y' = f(y)</m>, depending only on <m>y</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y' = x + y</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This depends explicitly on <m>x</m>, so it is not autonomous.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y' = e^{x} y^{2}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Not autonomous because of the <m>e^{x}</m> factor.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-autonomous-2">
  <title>Equilibrium Solutions</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For the autonomous equation <m>y' = y(2-y)</m>, which of the following are equilibrium solutions?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>y = 0</m> and <m>y = 2</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Equilibria occur where <m>f(y)=0</m>, so <m>y(2-y)=0</m> gives <m>y=0,2</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 1</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>At <m>y=1</m>, <m>y'=1(1)=1</m>, so it is not an equilibrium.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>No equilibrium solutions</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect—two exist.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-autonomous-3">
  <title>Stability From the Sign of <m>f'(y)</m></title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider <m>y' = y(3-y)</m>.  Determine the stability of the equilibrium <m>y = 3</m>.
      Use the sign of <m>f'(y)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>Stable, because <m>f'(3) = -3</m> is negative.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. For autonomous equations, an equilibrium <m>y=A</m> is stable if <m>f'(A)&lt;0</m>.  
          Here <m>f(y)=y(3-y)</m> gives <m>f'(y)=3-2y</m>, so <m>f'(3)=-3&lt;0</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Unstable, because <m>f'(3) = 3</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this computes the derivative incorrectly.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Neither stable nor unstable</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect—its stability is determined by <m>f'(3)</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-autonomous-4">
  <title>Solving a Simple Autonomous ODE</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the IVP <m>y' = 2y</m>, <m>y(0)=5</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>y = 5e^{2x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Integrate <m>y'/y = 2</m> to get <m>y=Ce^{2x}</m>,  
          then apply <m>y(0)=5</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 5e^{x/2}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect exponent.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 2e^{5x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect constant and exponent.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-autonomous-5">
  <title>Interpreting a Phase Line</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For an autonomous equation <m>y' = f(y)</m>, suppose the phase line shows arrows pointing 
      toward <m>y=1</m> from both above and below.  What does this indicate?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>y = 1</m> is a stable equilibrium.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. When trajectories move toward an equilibrium from both sides, 
          that equilibrium is stable.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 1</m> is an unstable equilibrium.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—unstable equilibria repel nearby solutions.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>There is no equilibrium at <m>y=1</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the phase line arrows imply an equilibrium there.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="autonomous-compare-solns">
  <statement>
    <p>
      How does the solution to the autonomous IVP 
      <m>\frac{dy}{dx}=\sin(y),\; y(-3)=1</m> 
      compare to the solution of the IVP 
      <m>\frac{dy}{dx}=\sin(y),\; y(1)=1</m>?  
      Can you generalize this idea for any autonomous equation?  
      A slope field for <m>y'=\sin(y)</m> is given in <xref ref="AutonomousSlopeField2026a"/>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="AutonomousSlopeField2026a" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>A slope field for <m>y'=\sin(y)</m>.</caption>
      <image source="AutonomousSlopeField2026a.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>
          A slope field with horizontal direction depending only on <m>y</m>; slopes vary by the 
          vertical position but are constant along horizontal lines, as is typical for autonomous 
          equations.
        </description>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Because the equation is autonomous (the slope depends only on <m>y</m> and not on <m>x</m>), 
      the two solutions differ only by a horizontal shift.  
      Both IVPs start with <m>y=1</m>, and all solution curves through <m>y=1</m> follow exactly 
      the same shape in the slope field.  
      The only difference is <em>where</em> on the <m>x</m>-axis the solution meets that level.
    </p>

    <p>
      In general, for any autonomous equation <m>y'=f(y)</m>, if two initial values share the same 
      <m>y</m>-coordinate but occur at different <m>x</m>-values, then the corresponding solutions 
      are identical up to horizontal translation.  
      This is because the slope at each point depends only on <m>y</m>, so moving left or right 
      simply shifts the solution curve without changing its shape.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="autonomous-equilibrium-constant">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Values of <m>y_0</m> for which <m>f(y_0)=0</m> are called 
      <term>critical points</term>.  
      They provide <term>equilibrium</term> solutions of the autonomous equation 
      <m>\frac{dy}{dx}=f(y)</m>, i.e. <m>y(x)\equiv y_0</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Why are equilibrium solutions constant solutions?  
      (Hint: Remember the result of the previous problem.)
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      If <m>f(y_0)=0</m>, then substituting <m>y(x)\equiv y_0</m> gives
    </p>

    <me>
      y'(x) = f(y_0) = 0.
    </me>

    <p>
      This differential equation says the slope is zero for all <m>x</m>, so the function must 
      remain constant.  
      Geometrically (as in the previous problem), the slope field has horizontal segments at that 
      <m>y</m>-value, and any solution starting there stays on that horizontal line for all time.  
      Thus equilibrium solutions are constant solutions.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="autonomous-equilibria-stability">
  <statement>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Determine the equilibrium solutions to 
            <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = y^{2} - y - 2.</m>  
            Use the slope field shown in <xref ref="AutonomousSlopeField2026b"/> 
            to confirm your finding.
          </p>

          <figure xml:id="AutonomousSlopeField2026b" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
            <caption>A slope field for <m>y'=y^2 - y -2</m>.</caption>
            <image source="AutonomousSlopeField2026b.jpg" width="50%">
              <description>
                A slope field with nearly horizontal slopes at the equilibrium levels, and steeper 
                slopes further away, typical of a cubic‑like autonomous ODE.
              </description>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Solution curves often approach or move away from equilibrium solutions as <m>x</m> 
            increases; this is called <term>stability</term>.
          </p>
          <ol maker="(a)">
            <li><p>If nearby solutions approach <m>y_0</m>, the equilibrium is a <term>sink</term> (stable).</p></li>
            <li><p>If some nearby solutions do not approach <m>y_0</m>, the equilibrium is <term>unstable</term>.</p></li>
            <li><p>If all nearby solutions move away, the equilibrium is a <term>source</term> (unstable).</p></li>
          </ol>

          <p>
            Determine the stability of the two equilibrium solutions 
            <m>y_1(x)\equiv -1</m> and <m>y_2(x)\equiv 2</m> for 
            <m>\displaystyle y'=y^2 - y -2.</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <ol>

      <li>
        <p>
          Solve <m>y^{2}-y-2=0</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
          (y-2)(y+1)=0.
        </me>

        <p>
          Thus the equilibrium solutions are <m>y=-1</m> and <m>y=2</m>.  
          In the slope field, horizontal segments occur at exactly these values.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><strong>Stability analysis.</strong></p>

        <p>
          Let <m>f(y)=y^{2}-y-2</m>. Then <m>f'(y)=2y-1</m>.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              At <m>y=-1</m>:
            </p>
            <me>
              f'(-1) = -2 - 1 = -3 &lt; 0.
            </me>
            <p>
              Negative derivative means nearby solutions move <em>toward</em> <m>-1</m>;  
              thus <m>y=-1</m> is a <strong>stable equilibrium</strong> (sink).
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              At <m>y=2</m>:
            </p>
            <me>
              f'(2) = 4 - 1 = 3 &gt; 0.
            </me>
            <p>
              Positive derivative means nearby solutions move <em>away</em> from <m>2</m>;  
              thus <m>y=2</m> is an <strong>unstable equilibrium</strong> (source).
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>

      </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="infection-model-autonomous">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A disease is spreading through a country.  
      Let <m>x</m> be the number of infected people, and <m>S</m> the number of susceptible 
      people.  
      The infection rate <m>\frac{dx}{dt}</m> is proportional to the product of the number of 
      infected people <m>x</m> and the number of susceptible people <m>S - x</m>.
    </p>

    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li><p>Write down the differential equation.</p></li>
      <li><p>Suppose <m>x(0)&gt;0</m>.  Compute <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t\to\infty} x(t)</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p>Does this result agree with your intuition?  Explain.</p></li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <ol marker="(a)">

      <li>
        <p>
          The rate is proportional to <m>x(S-x)</m>, so the model is
        </p>

        <me>
          \frac{dx}{dt} = k\, x(S-x),
        </me>

        <p>
          where <m>k&gt;0</m> is the infection constant.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          This logistic‑type equation has equilibria at <m>x=0</m> and <m>x=S</m>.  
          For <m>x(0)&gt;0</m>, the solution increases and approaches the carrying capacity 
          <m>S</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
          \lim_{t\to\infty} x(t) = S.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Yes—this matches intuition.  
          As long as some people are initially infected, eventually everyone susceptible 
          becomes infected in this simplified model, so the number of infected tends toward 
          <m>S</m>.  
          Real disease dynamics can be more complicated, but in this autonomous model 
          the infection saturates the susceptible population.
        </p>
      </li>

    </ol>

  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives16">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
     Analyze stability of equilibrium points by determining whether nearby solutions move toward or away from them.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
     Describe long‑term behavior of solutions (e.g., convergence to stable equilibria, divergence from unstable ones) using graphical evidence alone.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Interpret models such as Newton’s cooling law and the logistic equation to understand how nonlinear autonomous equations can produce qualitatively different dynamics.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>